          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>1315</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-2.2</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-2.2.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Hodge Theory II › Hodge structures › Hodge theory"><fr:link type="local" href="hodge-theory-ii-2.xml" addr="hodge-theory-ii-2" title="Hodge Theory II › Hodge structures"><fr:link type="local" href="hodge-theory-ii.xml" addr="hodge-theory-ii" title="Hodge Theory II">Hodge Theory II</fr:link> › Hodge structures</fr:link> › Hodge theory</fr:title>
            <fr:authors />
            <fr:number>2.2</fr:number>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>1225</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-2.2.1</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-2.2.1.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>2.2.1</fr:number>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> be a compact Kähler variety (for example, smooth and projective).
    By the holomorphic Poincaré lemma, the de Rham complex <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Omega _X^\bullet ]]></fr:tex> is a resolution of the constant sheaf <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex>.
    We thus have an isomorphism (<fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-1.4.2" href="hodge-theory-ii-1.4.2.xml" number="1.4.2" />)
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       \operatorname {H}^\bullet (X,\mathbb {C})       \sim  \operatorname {\mathbb {H}}^\bullet (X,\Omega _X^\bullet )     ]]></fr:tex>
    and the stupid filtration on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Omega _X^\bullet ]]></fr:tex> (<fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-1.4.5" href="hodge-theory-ii-1.4.5.xml" number="1.4.5" />) defines the hypercohomology spectral sequence

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>507</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-2.2.1.1</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-2.2.1.1.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>2.2.1.1</fr:number></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         E_1^{pq}         = \operatorname {H}^q(X,\Omega _X^q)         \Rightarrow  \operatorname {H}^{p+q}(X,\mathbb {C})       \tag{2.2.1.1}       ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>

    which abuts to the <fr:em>Hodge filtration</fr:em> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {H}^\bullet (X,\mathbb {C})]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
                <fr:p>By Hodge theory [<fr:link type="local" href="H1952.xml" addr="H1952" title="The theory and applications of harmonic integrals">H1952</fr:link>; <fr:link type="local" href="W1958.xml" addr="W1958" title="Introduction à L'Étude des Variétés Kählériennes">W1958</fr:link>], we have:

    
 <html:ol xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(A) &quot;">
        The spectral sequence <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-2.2.1.1" href="hodge-theory-ii-2.2.1.1.xml" taxon="Equation" number="2.2.1.1" /> degenerates: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E_1=E_\infty ]]></fr:tex>.
      </html:li>

      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(B) &quot;">
        The Hodge filtration of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {H}^n(X,\mathbb {C})]]></fr:tex> is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>-opposite to the complex conjugate filtration.
      </html:li>

    </html:ol></fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>1226</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-2.2.2</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-2.2.2.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>2.2.2</fr:number>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V]]></fr:tex> be a local system of real vector spaces over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>, i.e. a sheaf of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex>-vector spaces that is locally isomorphic to a constant sheaf <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {R}^n]]></fr:tex>.
    Suppose that there exists on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V]]></fr:tex> a bilinear form
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       Q\colon  V\otimes  V\to \mathbb {R}     ]]></fr:tex>
    that is locally constant and <fr:em>defined</fr:em>.
    If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> is connected, this is the case if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V]]></fr:tex> is defined by a representation of a finite quotient of the fundamental group of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
                <fr:p>Statements (A) and (B) <fr:link type="local" href="hodge-theory-ii-2.2.1.xml" addr="hodge-theory-ii-2.2.1">above</fr:link> remain true as they are, without needing to change the proofs, for cohomology with coefficients in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V_\mathbb {C}=V\otimes _\mathbb {R}\mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex>, since the spectral sequence
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       E_1^{pq}       = \operatorname {H}^q(X,\Omega _X^p(V))       \Rightarrow  \operatorname {H}^{p+q}(X,V_\mathbb {C})     ]]></fr:tex>
    induced by the de Rham resolution of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V_\mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Omega _X^\bullet (V_\mathbb {C})]]></fr:tex> degenerates, and abuts to a filtration on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {H}^n(X,V_\mathbb {C})]]></fr:tex> that is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>-opposite to the complex conjugate filtration.</fr:p>
                <fr:p>The vector space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {H}^n(X,V)]]></fr:tex> is thus endowed with a canonical real Hodge structure of weight <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>1227</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-2.2.3</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-2.2.3.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>2.2.3</fr:number>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>We show in [<fr:link type="local" href="D1968.xml" addr="D1968" title="Théorème de Lefschetz et critères de dégénérescence de suites spectrales">D1968</fr:link>] that the statements in <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-2.2.1" href="hodge-theory-ii-2.2.1.xml" number="2.2.1" /> remain true when <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> is a non-singular complete algebraic, not necessarily Kähler, variety.
    The proof from <fr:em>loc. cit.</fr:em>, based on a reduction to the projective case by Chow's lemma and resolution of singularities, extends to the case of <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-2.2.2" href="hodge-theory-ii-2.2.2.xml" number="2.2.2" />.</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>1228</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-2.2.4</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-2.2.4.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>2.2.4</fr:number>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {L}]]></fr:tex> be an invertible sheaf.
    Here are two ways of defining the class <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[c_1(\mathcal {L})]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
                <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
                  <fr:frontmatter>
                    <fr:anchor>1229</fr:anchor>
                    <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-2.2.4.1</fr:addr>
                    <fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-2.2.4.1.xml</fr:route>
                    <fr:authors />
                    <fr:number>2.2.4.1</fr:number>
                  </fr:frontmatter>
                  <fr:mainmatter>
                    <fr:p>The sheaf <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {L}]]></fr:tex> defines an element <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[c]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {H}^1(X,\mathcal {O}^*)]]></fr:tex>.
      Its image under <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {d} f/f\colon \mathcal {O}^*\to \Omega ^1]]></fr:tex> lies in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {H}^1(X,\Omega ^1)]]></fr:tex>.
      More precisely, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {d} f/f]]></fr:tex> defines a morphism of complexes
      <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         \mathrm {d}\log \colon          \mathcal {O}^*[-1]         \to  (0\to \Omega _X^1\to \Omega _X^2\to \ldots )         = \sigma _{\geqslant 1}(\Omega _X^\bullet ).       ]]></fr:tex>
      This complex maps to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Omega _X^\bullet ]]></fr:tex>, whence
      <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         \mathrm {d}\log \colon  \mathcal {O}^*[-1]\to \Omega _X^\bullet        ]]></fr:tex>
      and the image of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[c]]></fr:tex> under <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {d}\log ]]></fr:tex> is in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {\mathbb {H}}^2(\Omega _X^\bullet )]]></fr:tex>.
      This construction still makes sense for an algebraic variety over an arbitrary field <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[k]]></fr:tex>.
      For <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[k=\mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex>, we further have
      <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         \operatorname {H}^2(X,\mathbb {C})         \xrightarrow {\sim } \operatorname {\mathbb {H}}^2(X,\Omega _X^\bullet )       ]]></fr:tex>
      whence a class
      <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         c'_1(\mathcal {L}) \in  \operatorname {H}^2(X,\mathbb {C}).       ]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
                  </fr:mainmatter>
                  <fr:backmatter />
                </fr:tree>
                <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
                  <fr:frontmatter>
                    <fr:anchor>1230</fr:anchor>
                    <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-2.2.4.2</fr:addr>
                    <fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-2.2.4.2.xml</fr:route>
                    <fr:authors />
                    <fr:number>2.2.4.2</fr:number>
                  </fr:frontmatter>
                  <fr:mainmatter>
                    <fr:p>The exponential exact sequence
      <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         0         \to  \mathbb {Z}(1)         \to  \mathcal {O}         \to  \mathcal {O}^*         \to  0       ]]></fr:tex>
      
      defines a homomorphism
      <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         \partial \colon  \operatorname {H}^1(X,\mathcal {O}^*)\to \operatorname {H}^2(X,\mathbb {Z}(1))       ]]></fr:tex>
      whence a class
      <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         \partial  c         = c''_1(\mathcal {L}) \in  \operatorname {H}^2(X,\mathbb {Z}(1)).       ]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
                    <fr:p>If we have a choice of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i]]></fr:tex>, then this class is identified with
      <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         c'''_1(\mathcal {L}) \in  \operatorname {H}^2(X,\mathbb {Z})       ]]></fr:tex>
      and for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {L}=\mathcal {O}(D)]]></fr:tex>, this <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[c'''_1(\mathcal {L})]]></fr:tex> is exactly the integer cohomology class defined by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex> (with the orientations being defined by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i]]></fr:tex>).</fr:p>
                  </fr:mainmatter>
                  <fr:backmatter />
                </fr:tree>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>1231</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-2.2.5</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-2.2.5.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>2.2.5</fr:number>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>We will prove:

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1232</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-2.2.5.1</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-2.2.5.1.xml</fr:route><fr:authors /><fr:number>2.2.5.1</fr:number></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>For <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha ]]></fr:tex> the natural injection of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {Z}(1)]]></fr:tex> into <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex>, we have
        <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[           -\alpha  c''_1(\mathcal {L})           = c'_1(\mathcal {L}).         ]]></fr:tex></fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1233</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-2.2.5.2</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-2.2.5.2.xml</fr:route><fr:authors /><fr:number>2.2.5.2</fr:number></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>For <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\bta ]]></fr:tex> the natural injection of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {Z}]]></fr:tex> into <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex>, we have
        <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[           -\beta  c'''_1(\mathcal {L})           = \frac {1}{2\pi  i}c'_1(\mathcal {L}).         ]]></fr:tex></fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:p>
                <fr:p>We prove this by considering the following diagram of complexes, in which <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\approx ]]></fr:tex> denotes a quasi-isomorphism, and whose upper triangle anti-commutes up to homotopy:
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       \begin {CD}         \mathbb {C} @>\approx >> \Omega _X^\bullet  @<<< \sigma _{\geqslant 1}(\Omega _X^\bullet )       \\@| @. @|       \\\mathbb {C} @<<< (\mathbb {C}\to \mathcal {O}) @>\approx >\mathrm {d}> \sigma _{\geqslant 1}(\Omega _X^\bullet )       \\@AAA @AAA @AA{\mathrm {d}\log }A       \\\mathbb {Z}(1) @<<< (\mathbb {Z}(1)\to \mathcal {O}) @>\approx >\exp > \mathcal {O}^*[-1]       \end {CD}     ]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>1234</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-2.2.6</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-2.2.6.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>2.2.6</fr:number>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> be a non-singular projective variety of pure dimension <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>.
    A choice of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i]]></fr:tex> defines an orientation of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> and an isomorphism <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {Z}(1)\simeq \mathbb {Z}]]></fr:tex>.
    The corresponding trace morphism
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       \operatorname {H}^{2n}(X,\mathbb {Z}(n)) \to  \mathbb {Z}     ]]></fr:tex>
    that is induced does not depend on the choice of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
                <fr:p>By Hodge, for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i\leqslant  n]]></fr:tex>, the morphism
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       L^{n-i}       = -\wedge  c''_1(\mathcal {O}(1))^{n-i}\colon        \operatorname {H}^i(X,\mathbb {Z}) \to  \operatorname {H}^{2n-i}(X,\mathbb {Z}(n-i))     ]]></fr:tex>
    is an isomorphism, and, combined with Poincaré duality
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       \operatorname {H}^i(X,\mathbb {Z})\otimes \operatorname {H}^{2n-i}(X,\mathbb {Z}(n-i))       \to  \operatorname {H}^{2n}(X,\mathbb {Z}(n-i))       \to  \mathbb {Z}(-i)     ]]></fr:tex>
    gives a polarisation on the <fr:em>primitive part</fr:em> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Ker}(L^{n-i+1})]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {H}^i(X,\mathbb {Z})]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
                <fr:p>We thus deduce that the rational Hodge structures <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {H}^i(X,\mathbb {Q})]]></fr:tex> are polarisable.</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
      <fr:backmatter />
    </fr:tree>
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
