          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>1316</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-4.2.5</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-4.2.5.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:taxon>Proposition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:authors />
            <fr:number>4.2.5</fr:number>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
 <html:ol xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
    
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(i) &quot;">
      The category of algebraic continuous families of Hodge <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex>-structures on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> satisfies the conditions of <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-4.2.2" href="hodge-theory-ii-4.2.2.xml" number="4.2.2" />.
    </html:li>

    
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(ii) &quot;">
      If a continuous family <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> of Hodge structures on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> is such that its restriction to a dense Zariski open <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> is algebraic, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> is algebraic.
    </html:li>

    
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(iii) &quot;">
      If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  X\to  S]]></fr:tex> is smooth and proper, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {R} f_*\mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex> is algebraic.
    </html:li>

  </html:ol>

  
    
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1175</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="machine">#293</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-293.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:authors /></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>Claim (ii) is evident.
      We will prove (i).
      Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {C}_0]]></fr:tex> be the set of continuous families of Hodge structures on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> that are of the form <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {R} f_*\mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex> (with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> smooth and projective).
      Then:

      
 <html:ol xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
        
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(a) &quot;">
          By the Künneth formula
          <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[             \mathrm {R}(f\times  g)_*\mathbb {Q}             \simeq  \mathrm {R} f_*\mathbb {Q}\otimes \mathrm {R} g_*\mathbb {Q},           ]]></fr:tex>
          <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {C}_0]]></fr:tex> is stable under tensor products.
        </html:li>

        
        
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(b) &quot;">
          Since
          <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[             \mathrm {R}(f\sqcup  g)_*\mathbb {Q}             \simeq  \mathrm {R} f_*\mathbb {Q}\oplus \mathrm {R} g_*\mathbb {Q},           ]]></fr:tex>
          <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {C}_0]]></fr:tex> is stable under direct sums.
        </html:li>


        
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(c) &quot;">
          
          The homogeneous components of each <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H\in \operatorname {Ob}\mathcal {C}_0]]></fr:tex> are polarisable (cf. <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-2.2.6" href="hodge-theory-ii-2.2.6.xml" number="2.2.6" />).
        </html:li>


        
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(d) &quot;">
          The objects <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H\in \operatorname {Ob}\mathcal {C}_0]]></fr:tex> satisfy <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-4.2.2.3" href="hodge-theory-ii-4.2.2.3.xml" taxon="Condition" number="4.2.2.3" />, since
          <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[             \mathrm {R} f_*\mathbb {Q}             \simeq  \mathrm {R} f_*\mathbb {Z}\otimes \mathbb {Q}.           ]]></fr:tex>
        </html:li>


        
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(e) &quot;">
          The objects <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H\in \operatorname {Ob}\mathcal {C}_0]]></fr:tex> satisfy <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-4.2.2.4" href="hodge-theory-ii-4.2.2.4.xml" taxon="Condition" number="4.2.2.4" />, by <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-4.1.2" href="hodge-theory-ii-4.1.2.xml" taxon="Corollary" number="4.1.2" />.
        </html:li>

      </html:ol></fr:p>

    <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {C}_1]]></fr:tex> be the set of direct factors of objects of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {C}_0]]></fr:tex>.
      Then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {C}_1]]></fr:tex> is stable under tensor products, direct sums, and direct factors, and satisfies <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-4.2.2.2" href="hodge-theory-ii-4.2.2.2.xml" taxon="Condition" number="4.2.2.2" />, <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-4.2.2.3" href="hodge-theory-ii-4.2.2.3.xml" taxon="Condition" number="4.2.2.3" />, and <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-4.2.2.4" href="hodge-theory-ii-4.2.2.4.xml" taxon="Condition" number="4.2.2.4" />.
      Furthermore, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {Q}(-1)]]></fr:tex> is in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {C}_1]]></fr:tex>, in the form of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {R}^2 f_*\mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex> for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon \mathbb {P}_S^1\to  S]]></fr:tex> the projective bundle.
      The category <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {C}_2]]></fr:tex> consisting of the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H\otimes \mathbb {Q}(k)]]></fr:tex> (for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[k\in \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex>) thus satisfy all the conditions of <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-4.2.2" href="hodge-theory-ii-4.2.2.xml" number="4.2.2" />.</fr:p>

    <fr:p>To thus deduce (i), it suffices to note that, if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> is a continuous family of Hodge structures, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U]]></fr:tex> a dense Zariski open of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>, then a sub-object of, a polarisation on, or an integer lattice of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H|U]]></fr:tex> uniquely extend to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>

    <fr:p>We now prove (iii).
      If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  X\to  S]]></fr:tex> is smooth and projective, then there exists a dense Zariski open subset <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> along with a commutative diagram
      
  <fr:resource hash="ce6c0de1c1ca3aa7b40fa4f554bd2bc1"><fr:resource-content><fr:img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," /></fr:resource-content><fr:resource-source type="latex" part="preamble"><![CDATA[
    \usepackage {amsmath}
    \usepackage {amssymb}
    \usepackage {tikz-cd}
  ]]></fr:resource-source><fr:resource-source type="latex" part="body"><![CDATA[\begin {tikzcd}
        X' \ar [rr,"p"] \ar [dr,swap,"f'"]
        && X|U \ar [dl,"f|U"]
      \\& U
      \end {tikzcd}]]></fr:resource-source></fr:resource>

      with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f']]></fr:tex> smooth and projective, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex> birational and surjective (by applying Chow's lemma and the resolution of singularities to the generic fibre of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex>).
      The restriction map
      <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         p^*\colon  (\mathrm {R} f_*\mathbb {Q})|U \to  \mathrm {R} f'_*\mathbb {Q}       ]]></fr:tex>
      is thus a direct injection of continuous families of Hodge structures, with left inverse given by the Gysin morphism <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p_!]]></fr:tex>, whence the algebraicity of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {R} f_*\mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
